Happiness in Australia

For the project I choose Australia as a country of my interest for the investigation of happiness. Australians case is interesting because of the location of the country and the level of well-being in the country. Australia now is in top 10 most happy countries and the city of Melburn was rated as the most attractive and convenient city to live. However, recent research has shown the so-called happiness paradox in Australia: the level of wealth and income in the country is growing, while the rating of happiness is slightly have fallen. This can be explained by three factors: adaptation of income level through the time, social comparison with the others living conditions and the aspiration level. Also, in the article () there were interesting hypothesis that were proved, about the engagement in the charity or volunteer activity, which increase the happiness. What is more, they have shown that the health is directly associated with happiness feeling. In my case it is interesting to look at the nonlinear relation between financial wellbeing and happiness level, from what income position the happiness and satisfaction would stop their increase. According to the given articles, I have chosen the set of variables, which I will use for building regression models. They are subjective health and subjective financial wellbeing of the household, how family important in life, the active membership in charitable organizations, the scaled variable of feeling freedom, the number of children. These variables show some significant impact on the happiness index, while I also tried the variables of importance of the nature, attitude to divorce and the security in household which do not show the significant relation. Further I would concentrate my attention only on first stated variables.

Statistics and tests

I tested all variables on the normality of the distribution by Kolmogorov-Smirnoff test and reveal that most of the variables are not distributed normally, however the looking at the graphs the distribution of the variables seems to look close to the normal one. The relationship between variable health and freedom with happiness index was observed by looking at the boxplots, the overall tendency in that with the better evaluation of health and feeling of freedom the level of happiness is growing. In both variables there are slightly more answers about lack of freedom or worse subjective health. One thing should be noted, that while the health medians of the categories are steeply growing, the starting point of the freedom (1- feel lack of freedom) is rated as the moderate level of happiness, whereas the latter positions are significantly low. The chi-square test I use to determine relationship between the family importance variable and happiness (initially coded one). The significantly different categories was the low values of family and the low happiness level, which show that people who did not appreciate family are considerably less happy. People who appreciate family (3 position out of 4) also show the big difference from the expected result, which shows that they more answered that they are totally happy than others do. For the statistical evaluation of other variables correlation test (Pearson) was performed, all the variables show the positive correlation, with the difference strength of coefficients: charity 0,05 ; national 0,11; freedom 0,57; health 0,4; finance 0,55.

Hypothesis H1 People who appreciate family importance are happier than those who were not H2 People with better health level are happier than others H3 The higher financial situation is associated with higher happiness level H4 The higher feeling of freedom level is associated with higher happiness level H5 The higher feeling of household security is associated with higher happiness level H6 People who engage in charity and voluntary activity are happier than those who were not H7 People who appreciate nature importance are happier than those who were not H8 People who attached to the country are happier than those who were not Hypothesis H1 People who appreciate family importance are happier than those who were not H2 People with better health level are happier than others H3 The higher financial situation is associated with higher happiness level H4 The higher feeling of freedom level is associated with higher happiness level H5 The higher feeling of household security is associated with higher happiness level H6 People who engage in charity and voluntary activity are happier than those who were not H7 People who appreciate nature importance are happier than those who were not H8 People who attached to the country are happier than those who were not

I started building regression model from the combination of all chosen variables in the one model and then gradually remove the insignificant variables by the p-value. After it, I tried the two variants of interaction in the model and include the spline regression on the finance variable. All the Adjusted R-squares was more than 0,2. Now lets more deeply concentrate on the models and testing of their quality. Model 1 hap_index1~ health + free + charity + secure + finance + nature + national Model 2 hap_index1~ health + free + finance + national Model 3 hap_index1~ health + free + finance + national + child + family

All built models have a significant p-value: < 2.2e-16, which shows that the results are not random, and the models explained the approximately 50 % of variance according to the Adjusted R squared, the highest Adjusted R squared have the last model, which account for 0,5089. Variables which I choose for building the second model are the significantly important variables from the first model, according to the stars, which show which variables explain the most part of the variance. The last model is the final one, without interactions and nonlinear effect, all variables there are significant, so now I would check the quality of the model for the outliers, heteroscedasticity and multicollinearity.

Model 3 hap_index1 = 0.25 health + 0,2 free + 0,15 finance + 0,06 national + 0,03 child + 0,26 family

As the scaled values of happiness distribution is from -3 up to 1.5 , the coefficients get in the model significantly affect the variation of happiness index.

Linearity

The red line on the first plot is approximately horizontal on zero, which is a sigh of good linearity of the model ###Homogeneity of variance The first plot shows a little bit skewed to the right distribution of fitted values. Whereas the values are quite equally distributed along red horizontal line, there is still a little sign of non-constant variances in the residuals errors (heteroscedasticity). That is why I perform two tests to check the heteroscedasticity of the model, ncvTest and bptest show the extremely low values of p-value, proves the heteroscedasticity, however this is not so significant, because of p-value out of the normal value of rejection the hypothesis. Also, on the third graph the distribution of values is quite good for the given model. ###Normality of residuals and leverage The distribution of values on the leverage plot have extreme values and it is skewed to the left, which shows the high leverage. From the other side, the distribution on the Q-Q plot is normal and goes straight along the line and there is very little number of outliers. Moreover, the completed test on the residuals normal distribution present good results and prove that outliers do not significantly affect the results of the model. Tests for Bonferroni p-value for most extreme outliers and test for Multicollinearity showed that the model is not affected by the extreme outliers and that there is no multicollinearity among variables. As my models are not-nested, I use AIC (Aikake Information Criteria), which shows not big difference in numbers between models and that model show significant result.

Spline regression

Though according to the previous analysis, the non-linear effect in the model is not necessary, the task consider using one, so I decided to prove the non-linear effect of the finance variable, that should not be linear to see the happiness paradox. I choose spline regression, because it can help to identify the exact variation in distribution, using the high number of knots. The summary of the spline regression shows the significant effect on some divided knots, most of them are at the last knots, that shows that the high financial situation is associated with the high level of happiness. The graph, however, shows that there are sharp decrease in happiness index at the 7 and 8 values of finance variable, which can be explained by the lack of the data or that the respondents prefer to choose either average or high number in describing finance level. In that case people with the high financial level are less happy than with the average level, which can be a sign of Australian paradox. The non-linear effect on health shows also significant result. The line graph and model results are similar with the previous boxplot distribution, where the poor health is significantly correlated with the low happiness level, the effect on this variable is still very close to the linear one.

# Build the model
data_1 <- na.exclude(data_as)
knots1 <- quantile(data_1$health, p = c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75))
model_hel <- lm (happy_coded ~ bs(health, knots = knots1), data = data_1)
summary(model_hel)

Interaction and plots

I perform two models with the interaction effect, the Adjusted R-squared have decreased, but the p-value is still significant. So, the interactions are health and finance, number of child and family importance. The health and finance interaction show the significant linear result, which is seen from the interaction graphs, so I would concentrate my attention on the second interaction effect. The effect of number of children and family importance show also the significant interaction in the model, and the interaction plot reveal some interesting results.

Conclusions and results

The hypothesis about security of the household, appreciating the nature and engaging in charity did not confirmed, however charity coefficient in the model was positive, it could not be stated that this result is significant. Other hypotheses have been confirmed and show mostly positive correlational effect, the major predictors of the happiness index was health, finance, feeling of freedom and family importance. All in all, the level of happiness in Australia is rather high and can be explained by basic predictors of happiness and the financial paradox is slightly been seen through the analysis. The variable showing national attachment to country might not be worked for the case of Australia because of the many migrants to this country, the variable of love to the nature might not work in case of Australia because this country is very close to nature, however in comparison with other countries this predictor can be important.
